==Latin==
{{wikipedia|lang=la}}

===Etymology===
From {{term/t|la|*dẹ̄os}}, from {{etyl|OL.|la}} {{term|deiuos|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*deywós}} (cf. Welsh {{term|duw|lang=cy}}, Lithuanian {{term|dievas|lang=lt}}, {{etyl|fa|-}} {{term|دیو|tr=div|lang=fa}} ‘demon’), ''o''-stem derivative from {{term/t|ine-pro|*dyew-||sky, heaven}} (compare Latin {{term/t|la|diēs}}, Welsh {{term|dydd|lang=cy}}), from {{term/t|ine-pro|*dei-}} ‘to shine’. Doublet of {{term/t|la|dīvus}}; related to {{term|Iuppiter|Iūpiter|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|Classical}} {{IPA|/ˈdeus/|lang=la}}
* {{audio|la-cls-deus.ogg|Audio (Classical)}}

===Noun===
{{la-noun|deus|dei|deī|m|second}} (''nom. plural'' '''[[dei|deī]]''' or '''[[di|dī]]''')

# [[god]], [[deity]]
#* {{RQ:Cicero Catiline}}
#*: ''O '''di''' immortales, ubinam gentium sumus? Quam rem publicam habemus? In qua urbe vivimus?.''
#*:: O ye immortal '''gods''', where on earth are we? In what city are we living? What is the government we have?
#* {{RQ:Vulgate|Daniel|1|2}}
#*: {{...}} et asportavit ea in terram Sennaar in domum '''dei''' sui et vasa intulit in domum thesauri '''dei''' sui
#*:: "{{...}} which he carried into the land of Shinar to the house of his '''god'''; and he brought the vessels into the treasure house of his '''god'''."
#: ''In principio erat Verbum et Verbum erat apud '''Deum''' et '''Deus''' erat Verbum.''
#:: In the beginning was the Word and the Word was with '''God''' and '''God''' was the Word.
# an imperial epithet (for [[deify|deified]] emperors)
# {{inflection of|deus||voc|s|lang=la}}

